<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-27T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-27T18:00:00-05:00" n="1285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1285">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.115/312</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">El Paso</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-27T16:00:00-07:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 27, 1917, 4 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Telegram today from Chihuahua agent to American S. and R. Company office
                            here that authorities there have assessed company five thousand pesos as
                            part of forced loan to pay troops, also expressing belief that train
                            service between Chihuahua and Juarez would be resumed immediately. See
                            my June 26, 4 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d1285fn2">Not printed.</note> and
                            June 27, noon.<note n="2" xml:id="d1285fn3">Not printed.</note>
                            Confirmatory information from others of forced loan.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cobb</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>